Steps 6-7 of FIGURE 29.9: Oxidation, Phosphorylation, and Dephosphorylation - 29.6 Conversion of Pyruvate to Acetyl CoA
The key structural element in thiamin diphosphate is the thiazolium ring-a five-membered, unsaturated heterocycle containing a sulfur atom and a positively charged nitrogen atom. The thiazolium ring is weakly acidic, with a $\mathrm{p} K_{\mathrm{a}}$ of approximately 18 for the ring hydrogen between N and S . Bases can therefore deprotonate thiamin diphosphate, leading to formation of an ylide much like the phosphonium ylides used in Wittig reactions (Section 19.11). As in the Wittig reaction, the TPP ylide is a nucleophile and adds to the ketone carbonyl group of pyruvate to yield an alcohol addition product.



$$
\text { Pyruvate } \begin{gathered}
\text { Thiamin } \\
\text { diphosphate } \\
\text { ylide }
\end{gathered}
$$

